# Mermaid Diagrams

Use Mermaid for all architecture diagrams. Follow C4 model thinking (Context, Container, Component levels) but use **basic Mermaid syntax** — `flowchart`, `sequenceDiagram`, `erDiagram`, etc.

## Do NOT use C4 macros

The `C4Context`, `C4Container`, `C4Component` diagram types and their macros (`Person()`, `System()`, `System_Ext()`, `System_Boundary()`, `Container()`, `ContainerDb()`, `Rel()`) render poorly. Avoid them entirely.

Instead, represent C4 concepts with standard Mermaid:

| C4 concept | Mermaid equivalent |
|---|---|
| Person | Node with person-shaped icon or a labeled rectangle |
| System / Container | Rectangle node, optionally in a subgraph |
| External system | Rectangle with "(external)" or similar label suffix |
| System boundary | `subgraph` |
| Database | Cylinder node `[(label)]` |
| Relationship | Arrow `-->` with label |

## Example — Context diagram

```mermaid
flowchart TB
    User["Insurance Manager"]
    Contributor["Contributor"]

    Coordinate["Coordinate PWA"]

    InsurerPortals["Insurer Portals (external)"]
    HCSAPortals["HCSA/PHSP Portals (external)"]

    User -->|"manages claims"| Coordinate
    Contributor -->|"submits receipts"| Coordinate
    User -->|"submits/checks claims"| InsurerPortals
    User -->|"submits HCSA claims"| HCSAPortals
```

## General rules

- Keep diagrams readable — favour clarity over completeness.
- Use `subgraph` for boundaries (browser, deployment unit, architectural layer).
- Use dashed arrows `-.->` for "implements" or optional relationships.
- Use solid arrows `-->` for runtime calls and data flow.
- Do not use explicit colors or styling — let the theme handle it.
